"# Chapter 5 — Environments and bindings: what does the program know right now?

An environment is a chain of frames. Each frame is a set of name-to-value bindings. When Scheme evaluates a symbol, it walks the chain from the innermost frame outward looking for a matching binding. That walk is the whole of lexical scope.

Motoi lets you see the chain. You can enumerate the current env's bindings, walk into a parent env, open a closure to see its captured bindings, and distinguish a top-level define from a let-binding buried in a lambda body. This chapter shows how.

If you have never thought of Scheme's lexical scope as a walkable data structure, this chapter will change how you read code. Every binding you have ever created lives in a frame, and every frame is queryable.

## 5.1 What is an environment?

An environment is an object with two fields: a set of bindings and a pointer to a parent environment.

```
env = { vars: Map(name -> value), parent: env-or-null }
```

The root env is the base env — where `car`, `cdr`, `map`, and all the primitive verbs live. When you start a Motoi REPL, this is the env you land in.

Every time you enter a new lexical scope — inside a `let`, inside a `lambda`, inside a `letrec` — a fresh child env is created. The child inherits from its parent by pointing at it. When evaluation looks up a name, it checks the child first, then walks up to the parent, then the grandparent, until it either finds the name or falls off the top.

This is what \"lexical scope\" means. It is not magic. It is a linked list of frames.

Motoi's env is implemented in `src/interp.js`. The `Env` class holds a `vars` Map and a `parent` pointer. `Env.define(name, val)` adds a binding to the current frame. `Env.lookup(name)` walks the chain.

## 5.2 Enumerating the current env

Motoi provides `current-env` to get the current env as a value, and `env-vars` to enumerate its bindings as a list of name-value pairs.

```scheme
(current-env)
;; => #<env>

(env-vars (current-env))
;; => ((x . 42) (y . \"hello\") (make-greeting . #<procedure>) ...)
```

The list contains every binding in the current frame. Not the parent's bindings — just the frame you are in.

If you defined `x` and `y` at the top level, they show up in the base env's vars. If you defined them inside a `let`, they show up in the let's frame vars.

## 5.3 Walking to the parent

`env-parent` gives you the parent env.

```scheme
(env-parent (current-env))
;; => #<env>   (the parent, or nil if this is the root)
```

Walk all the way up:

```scheme
(define (walk-envs e)
  (if e
      (cons (env-vars e) (walk-envs (env-parent e)))
      '()))

(walk-envs (current-env))
;; => ( ((x . 42) (y . \"hello\"))
;;      ((car . #<procedure>) (cdr . #<procedure>) ... hundreds of primitives ...) )
```

The first element is your current frame; the last element is the base env with all the primitives.

