## 5.17 What you have so far

Even the seed of this chapter gives you enough to start.

You know an env is a chain of frames. You know how to get the current env (`current-env`), enumerate its bindings (`env-vars`), and walk to its parent (`env-parent`). You have a small script for walking the full chain.

Wave 2 will fill in the harder parts — closures, shadowing, free variables, testing patterns. Until then, the three verbs above are enough to start exploring.

## 5.18 Try it now

Type these at the REPL:

```scheme
(define x 42)
(define y \"hello\")
(env-vars (current-env))

(let ((z 100))
  (env-vars (current-env)))

(define (make-adder n)
  (lambda (x) (+ n x)))

(define add5 (make-adder 5))
(closure-env add5)      ;; the captured env
(env-vars (closure-env add5))
;; => ((n . 5))
```

The last block shows the introspection you will get once Wave 2 lands `closure-env`. For now, the first three snippets work with the base env introspection verbs.

