## 5.21 Deep-seed — why env introspection matters

Even the seed of this chapter deserves a section on motivation, because env introspection is easy to underappreciate until you need it.

Consider a bug you have hit before. You called a function. It returned the wrong value. You do not know why. The stepping debugger would let you pause and see local variables, but Motoi does not have a stepping debugger. What Motoi has is env introspection.

You wrap the suspicious call in a let that captures the env:

```scheme
(let ((env-snapshot (current-env)))
  (my-buggy-function 42)
  (display (env-vars env-snapshot)))
```

Now you have the local env at the moment of the call, printed out. Every binding, every value, in one view. That is what a stepping debugger would give you, but stripped down to just the env.

For most bugs, this is enough. You look at the values, spot the one that is wrong, and now you know what upstream code needs to be fixed. No breakpoints. No stepping. One introspection call.

## 5.22 Deep-seed — env and macros

Chapter 6 will cover macros. Here is a preview of how they interact with env introspection.

A macro expands to a form that is then evaluated in the current env. If the macro introduces a new binding, that binding lives in the surrounding env — potentially shadowing something the caller did not expect.

Env introspection lets you see this happen. Before the macro use, snapshot the env. After the macro expands and evaluates, snapshot again. Diff the two and you have found every binding the macro introduced.

This is the mechanical way to detect \"hygiene\" issues in macros — accidental capture where a macro introduces a name that collides with a name in the caller's env. Motoi's macros use gensym for auto-hygiene (see `src/macro.js`), but env introspection is the fallback when you want to verify.

## 5.23 Deep-seed — env and Cortex

Chapter 10 will cover Cortex introspection. Here is another preview.

An env holds transient bindings — they exist for the duration of a session. Cortex holds durable bindings — they exist across sessions. Together they are your program's memory: transient plus persistent.

Env introspection tells you what the program knows *right now*. Cortex introspection tells you what the program *has known across time*. Both queries are one verb call away.

A common pattern is to snapshot part of the env into Cortex at the end of a session, so the next session can restore it:

```scheme
(define (checkpoint-env)
  (for-each
    (lambda (binding)
      (cortex/write :key (car binding) :value (cdr binding)))
    (env-vars (current-env))))
```

Now next session's first move can be `(restore-env)` and pick up where you left off. Env plus Cortex plus introspection over both gives you programs that remember what they were doing.

