## 5.25 Deep-seed — a taste of closures

Since closures are the star of the full chapter, one more taste before Wave 2.

A closure is a procedure that captured some bindings from its defining scope. `(lambda (x) (+ x n))` is a closure over `n` — it remembers whatever `n` was when it was created.

```scheme
(define (make-counter)
  (let ((count 0))
    (lambda ()
      (set! count (+ count 1))
      count)))

(define c1 (make-counter))
(c1)  ;; => 1
(c1)  ;; => 2
(c1)  ;; => 3
```

Each call to `(c1)` finds `count` in its captured env, updates it, returns the new value. The `count` binding is not visible from the outside; it lives inside the closure.

Wave 2's `closure-env` verb will let you introspect that captured env. You will be able to type:

```scheme
(env-vars (closure-env c1))
;; => ((count . 3))
```

And see the captured `count` right there. No debugger. No breakpoint. One verb call.

That is what env introspection will give you when the chapter is fully authored. For now, the base verbs (`current-env`, `env-vars`, `env-parent`) are enough to start playing.

